board.com/images/posticons/pi_supermad.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Not crazy about the responses</span><hr size=1> I could never in a million years do tech support. I work for a small-ish engineering firm (about 15 people). I build, fix, and maintain all of our computers here. I also manage our servers, the VPN, exchange server etc., etc. I have to be nice to these people because I work with them every day. Thankfully they're all smart enough to just let me do my thing with minimal hassle whenever something goes wrong. Something breaks, I fix it, The End.<br>
<br>
But even so, I get enough of a taste of the frustration of doing tech support that I know I don't have anywhere near enough patience/diplomacy to deal with that.<br>
<br>
My biggest pet peeve is this:<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Valued Employee:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> I was working with &lt;Application X&gt; when I got some error message and I had to close it and start &lt;Application X&gt; again.<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Me:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Is it doing it now?<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Valued Employee:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> No, it's working fine now.<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Me:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Do you know what the error message said?<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Valued Employee:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> No. It said something about an error. I don't know what it meant.<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Me:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> ...<br>
<br>
Please for the love of all that is holy, if you have a computer problem that involves an error message, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>write it down</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. It's not just &quot;a bunch of gibberish&quot;, ok? Just because <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>you</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> don't understand it doesn't mean that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>I</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> won't. If you can't tell me what the problem is, I can't help you.<br>
<br>
My other annoyances are mostly minor. I had this one guy (contract employee who thankfully no longer works here) who consistantly referred to the desktop PC we used as a file server as &quot;the mainframe&quot;. Whenever he would refer to using Power Desk or Windows Explorer to browse the F: drive (the file server), that was called &quot;logging on to the mainframe&quot;. Yeah, I know; it's not a big deal. But after hearing that every day for a few months, I was starting to go crazy. It would be like if you were a mechanic and you had this one cusomter who insists on calling his van an SUV. Eventually it's like someone running their nails down a chalkboard. And you want to correct him, but you know it's just not worth it.<br>
<br>
This was the same guy who never did understand why he couldn't just bring his laptop from home and have it automagically work with our Win2k domain. I tried explaining to him as simply as I could that joining our computer network would require me to either do things to his laptop that would make it not work at home, or I would have to drop all of our network's security; neither of which I was willing to do. I finally just had to tell him that joining our network wasn't like joining a country club - it's like joining a cult. Once you're in, there's no getting out. I don't think he really got that, either, but the questions stopped after that  <br>
<br>
And just to add more fuel to the fire, here's the Bastard Operator From Hell archives:<br>
