<br>
1) the mute button is your friend... use it.<br>
2) venting everywhere else but at the customer is a -good- thing so you can be calm, collected, and nice to the customer.  THAT customer hasn't asked that inane question 50 million times, but you have had 50 million customers within a span of 10 minutes who have asked that exact same inane question.<br>
3) They go away.  When I was subteaching, this got me through some narly classes... 50 mins and they go away.  With tech support, it was even shorter.  Thus, I could be nice and pleasant for that time firm in the knowledge they would go away and not be heard from again.<br>
<br>
As for customers..... I worked phone tech support for a company that OEMed scanners, one of the 3 lowest priced in the market at the time (they are now out of business).  I have worked tech support calls with grocery store manages and grocery wholesalers for EFT (electronic fund transfer... using plastic to pay for stuff) software/hardware.  I have also been tech support to the tech support for EFT stuff.  The absolute worst of that was tech support for tech support.  You know you have specifically sent information to the individual.  You have confirmation the individual opened the document.  You sent it less than 10 mins ago (so it wasn't like they could have read it a month or two ago and forgotten) and they ask you the same exact damn question you have covered very sepcifically in the FAQ.  In fact, when you read the exact text of the FAQ to him (asking him to open his document so he sees it as well) he fully understands it and it answers exactly what he needs.  ARGH!!!  that coupled with the fact most of the tech support was pretty clueless on how computers worked, even how to format a floppy diskette (which they did need to do on occassion).  Worse, the one person who was -the- most inept at any computer knowledge was promoted and the one who actually knew stuff and worked his tail off getting things accomplished was laid off (long before I was laid off, so I am not referring to me). Gahhhhhh!<br>
<br>
BOFH = Bastard Operator from hell.  It's the series of essays written by a sysadmin of the things we would -love- to do but actually don't.  It is written for humor, to get through the harrowing stuff with a bit of grin while retaining a nice, calm, happy demenur to the customer.<br>
<br>
RTFM = Read the Fucking/Fine Manual.  99% of -all- problems can easily be solved with reading the printed material which came with the product and/or looking for support information on the website of the manufacturer.  <br>
<br>
